This header seems to be missing:

    #include <stdint.h> // uint8_t
    #include <stdlib.h> // size_t
    #include "legato.h" // LE_SHARED, le_result_t

I think legato.h sucks in the other two as well, so I guess this could just do #include "legato.h"

I spoke with Jen on Slack and he posted some of this in a Slack chat, but I'll repeat it here so that all of the necessary information is available here on gerrit.

The above solution is required because the Legato event loop of this task must be running so that the notification handlers registered to the DataHub can be processed in this task.  In addition to the changes described in my previous comment, I also think you should add this to your hl78 uart transport:

    bool UartTransport::hasMessage(void)
    {
        return (serial_number_of_bytes_waiting(m_sHandle) > 0);
    }

Also, I think that the underlyingReceive should be implemented in terms of serial_nonblocking_read so that a reasonable timeout for the read can be specified.  If the bytes are not available in this time, then underlyingReceive can return an error.  This typically won't happen because underlyingReceive will only be called by erpc_server_poll if hasMessage returned true.

Just a style observation (no need to change if you disagree), but I would write:

    return (xSemaphoreTake(m_sem, timeout / 1000 / portTICK_PERIOD_MS) == pdTRUE);

Why? 1 line vs 4 and single return vs multiple return.

What about this?

    erpc_status_t UartTransport::init(const sHuart *uartSettings)
    {
        // NOTE: it is necessary to take a copy of the settings because Altair's serial_open
        // requires a pointer to mutable data even though it does not (and should not) perform
        // any mutations on that data.
        sHuart writableSettings = *uartSettings;
        m_sHandle = serial_open(&writeableSettings);
        // ...
    }

Why I prefer the above approach:
* It lets the client choose which UART to operate the transport over
* It lets the client choose the UART settings to use (including whether or not they want to call serial_load_defconfig)
* It eliminates the m_uartInitParam member variable of the class.  Note that this variable didn't need to be scoped to the object lifetime previously since the variable is only used within the scope of this method.

This is an unnecessary heap allocation that will leak memory since the variable isn't deleted.  This could instead just be created on the stack like this:

    sHuart uartInitParam = {0};
    if (serial_load_defconfig(ACTIVE_UARTF1, &uartInitParam) != 0)
    {
        // ...

Use a for loop to initialize it so if we add a new bus to i2c_BusId_t list, there willbe no need to update this piece of code.

BusIdToSwitchRegMap[0] = 0;
for( i=1; i < I2C_NUM_BUSSES ; i++)
{
    BusIdToSwitchRegMap[i] = ( 1 << ( i - 1 ) );
}

This is fine as-is, but I just realized that this might be better expressed as:

    static const uint8_t BusIdToSwitchRegMap[I2C_NUM_BUSSES] =
    {
        [I2C_BUS_MAIN] = 0, // all switch ports disabled
        [I2C_BUS_IOT_SLOT] = (1 << 0),
        [I2C_BUS_GPIO_EXPANDER] = (1 << 1),
        [I2C_BUS_BATTERY_GAUGE] = (1 << 2),
        [I2C_BUS_BATTERY_SENSORS] = (1 << 3),
    };

I prefer this because it only checks whether the character is '\r' in one spot.  Also, another minor thing is that I reduced the scope of "char c" by one level.  I always like to have variables declared in the smallest scope possible.

    char input[CMDBUF_LEN] = {0};
    for (uint32_t i = 0; i < (CMDBUF_LEN - 1); i++)
    {
        char c;
        LE_ASSERT(serial_read(sHandle, &c, 1) == 1);
        if (c == '\r')
        {
            break;
        }
        input[i] = c;
    }

Is there a reason why you advance a pointer and a counter rather than using the counter as an array offset like this?

    for (size_t i = 0; i < NUM_ARRAY_MEMBERS(PinList); i++)
    {
        if (PinList[i].handle && PinList[i].id == id)
        {
            return &PinList[i];
        }
    }

I'm not trying to nit-pick on style.  I'm just wondering if there is a reason why you didn't write it the way I did.

This function feels like a half-measure.  It's useful, but only in the situation where the message is a string that is available to the client.  So it's useful for ReportError("Invalid state transition\n"), but can't be used as ReportError("Invalid state transition from state %s to %s\n", StateName(fromState), StateName(toState));

There are lots of instances where the latter use case would be applicable.  What do you think of this?

    void PrintError(const char *fmt, ...)
    {
        va_list args;
        va_start(args, fmt);
        printf("**ERROR: ");
        vprintf(fmt, args);
        va_end(args);
    }

Why not this?

    LE_ASSERT(channel >= 0 && channel < DIO_NUM_CHANNELS);

Isn't it a programming error to call this function with an invalid channel ID?

This is a personal preference, but I find it easier to read if code like this:

    int res = doSomething();
    if (res != OK)
    {
        LOG("failed");
        return SOME_ERROR;
    }
    else
    {
        more();
        stuff();
        return OK;
    }

is written as:

    int res = doSomething();
    if (res != OK)
    {
        LOG("failed");
        return SOME_ERROR);
    }

    more();
    stuff();
    return OK;

It seems like the above code is trying to implement a default case, but doing so in an unusual way.  Maybe this?

    switch (mode)
    {
        case DIO_TRIGGER_RISING:
            handle->state = DIO_STATE_TRIGGER_RISING;
            break;
        // ...
        default:
            LE_CRIT("Invalid mode!\n");
            return LE_BAD_PARAMETER;
    }
    // TODO: trigger handlers
    return LE_OK;

I guess maybe you're trying to force the compiler to issue a warning for a non-exhaustive switch statement in the event that a new enum field is added.  Personally, I would pick the more idiomatic switch statement because we would still have to search everywhere in the code for switch statements like this if an enum value is added because we can't guarantee that every conditional or switch statement was constructed in a way that will generate a warning due to the new enum value.
